        <pb n="5641" facs="#L1916_2179_img_5641"/>
            <text type="letter" decls="#corresp1">
                <body>
                    

<opener><dateline><date>11<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> Jan. 1916</date></dateline>
<salute>My dearest mother &#x2014;</salute></opener> <p>we are now back in
<lb/> our old quarters &amp; what a dreary spot it is
<lb/> compared with the place we left. We arrived 
<lb/> on Saturday &amp; were told we should find that
<lb/> the previous Division had carried out all
<lb/> kinds of improvements but of course as we
<lb/> quite expected, practically nothing had been done
<lb/> in this direction.</p><p> There is a very big scheme
<lb/> now on foot to improve all the billeting areas
<lb/> so as to make them more comfortable for the
<lb/> men &#x2014; for instance repairing buildings, constructing 
<lb/> wash houses, drying rooms, incinerators, etc etc. 
<lb/> The regiments are therefore being largely employed
<lb/> on this work &amp; if it is not exactly soldiering it
<lb/> is a welcome change to the continual training.
<lb/> Machine Gunmen &amp; Grenadiers however have
<lb/> to continue at their own special work &#x2014; I rather
<lb/> wish it was otherwise as it would be a pleasant
<lb/> change to be turned on to something new. </p><p>You
<lb/> have no idea how deadly dull it is here.
<lb/> Imagine what it would be like to be in a
<lb/> little village about the size of Portaferry, with
<lb/> no railway near at hand &amp; away from the 
<lb/> sea. </p><p>When we came here for the first time
        
    

    
         
        <pb n="5642" facs="#L1916_2179_img_5642"/>
        
        
           
            <lb/>it did not seem so bad but to return here
<lb/> after being in a good area is very disagreeable &#x2014;
<lb/> we should all have much <sic>prefered</sic> going back to
<lb/> the trenches. </p><p>Yesterday I had rather a 
<lb/> nasty bilious turn &#x2014; very sick all day &amp; headache
<lb/> so had to stay in bed. Think some of our 
<lb/> food must have been bad as 2 others on the H. Q
<lb/> Staff were also feeling off colour. Today however
<lb/> I have <add>been</add> practically all right again &amp; able to be about
<lb/> as usual.</p><p> The parcel from Thompsons &#x2014; I
<lb/>mean Malcolmsons &#x2014; arrived all right &amp; also one
<lb/> from Pattersons &amp; I have just been told there is
<lb/> a small wood box for me in the Bde. office which
<lb/> is probably the one with apples from home. Thanks
<lb/> ever so much for all. </p><p>Would you please send
<lb/> me by post 2 tins of solid Methylated Spirit for my
<lb/> "Little Kitchener" Lamp. You will be able to get it in
<lb/> Mitchells.</p><p> Was so glad to hear from your last
<lb/> letter that Kathleen is getting along all right though  I
<lb/> am sure it must be very tedious for her that the
<lb/> progress is so slow.</p><p> With my fondest
<lb/>love to all</p>
<closer><salute>Your loving son</salute>
<signed>Jim</signed></closer>
        
    
        
        
        
    
                </body>
            </text>

        
            
        
            
        
            
